    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n                <jats:sec>\n                  <jats:title>Purpose</jats:title>\n                  <jats:p>Comparing seroprevalence and antibody kinetics in three different commercially available assays for SARS-CoV-2.</jats:p>\n                </jats:sec>\n                <jats:sec>\n                  <jats:title>Methods</jats:title>\n                  <jats:p>Serostatus of COVID-19 patients was analyzed 5 months and 10 months after their infection, using three different assays: Diasorin LIAISON\u00ae, Euroimmun\u00ae, Abbott Diagnostics\u00ae ARCHITECT.</jats:p>\n                </jats:sec>\n                <jats:sec>\n                  <jats:title>Results</jats:title>\n                  <jats:p>Seropositivity at baseline differed significantly depending on the assay (Diasorin 81%, Euroimmun 83%, Abbott 59%). At follow-up antibody levels detected in the Diasorin assay were stable, while there was a significant loss in seropositivity in the Euroimmun and Abbott assays.</jats:p>\n                </jats:sec>\n                <jats:sec>\n                  <jats:title>Conclusion</jats:title>\n                  <jats:p>There are significant differences in SARS-CoV-2 antibody kinetics based on the specific assay used.</jats:p>\n                </jats:sec>\n                <jats:sec>\n                  <jats:title>Trial registration number, date of registration</jats:title>\n                  <jats:p>DRKS00022549, 29.07.2020 \u201cretrospectively registered\u201d</jats:p>\n                </jats:sec>",
